\begin_body

\begin_layout Chapter
The tethered fly assay 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olfactory stimuli can be decomposed into a few basic features, like the
 chemical identity of the odorants in the odor, their concnetration, and
 the kinetics of the stimulus.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acfp{ORN}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 appear to be able to capture all these features.
 The chemical identity of the odorant is captured by which olfactory neurons
 respond, since different neurons have different receptors.
 The concentration of the odorants in the stimulus is captured in part by
 the amplitude of neuronal response, and also by the identity of the neurons
 that respond, since different receptors have different sensitivities to
 the same odornt.
 Finally, the temporal structure of the odorant stimulus is encoded in the
 response kientics of neuron response.
 Insects on the wing can encounter odorant stimuli with varying cincbentrations
 and durations, and it is not clear if flies use all these features of the
 stimulus equally to make navigational decisions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{TFA}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, originally developed to study insect flight (cite Gotz) and later adapted
 and modified to study vision, mechanosensation, and the visual control
 of flight 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lehmann:1997vz,Frye:2001ev,Sherman:2003tg,Bender:2006wl,Budick:2007gx"

\end_inset

.
 Recently, the TFA has also been used to study olfaction, either in the
 fixed tethered configuration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bhandawat:2010eu"

\end_inset

 or in rotatable tethered configiration, where flies can actively reoirent
 into or away from an odorised airstream 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Frye:2003da,Frye:2004gj,Krishnan:2011eb"

\end_inset

.
 Since the fly is fixed in place in this assay, it allows delivering and
 measuring olfactroy stimuli and measuring how these olfactroy stimuli modualte
 olfactroy flight behavior.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next section, I detail my attempts to use this assay to determine
 how flies change their flight behaviour with the identitiy, ampliotude
 and duration of olfactroy stimuli.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bhandawat:2010eu"

\end_inset

, I constructed a tethered flight assay where flies are tehtered to insect
 pins and held in front of an airstream in the dark (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-schematic"

\end_inset

for a picture).
 A paired olfactometer used four valves, all upstream of vials containing
 odorant or control, to deliver short pulses of either odorant or control.
 A PID behind the fly captured the odorant delivered to the fly, and allowed
 me to record the stimulus simultenously with the behavior of the fly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
