Schematic of the tethered flight assay.
 
\emph default
A fly is tethered to a fine insect pin and suspended below a 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{IR}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{LED}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (see top left for a picture).
 The wings of the fly cast a shadow on two photo detectors below the fly,
 whose signals can be used to measure the frequnecy and amplitude of the
 fly's wing beats.
 An odorant delivery system (labelled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

design #1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can deliver either pulses of odorant or pulses of clean air to the fly.
 Valves switch between two symmetrical airstreams, one with odor (red) or
 one without, to deliver odorant to the fly with minimial changes in airflow.
 A 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{PID}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 sucks all the air and odorant delivered to the fly, allowing simultenous
 monitoring of the behavior and the stimulus.
 Finally, genetic strategies can be used to delete or replace receptors
 in the fly.
 The timeseries at the bottom shows the typical experiemntal block, where
 a control pulse (with no odorant) is presented first, followed by a test
 pulse with odorant.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Flight responses to pulses of different odorants 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Flies flapped their wings spontensouly when suspended in the device, creating
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

h√ºtchens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 waveform on the photodetector cell (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-diff-odors"

\end_inset

a).
 Each windbeat cycle produced this characteristic bilobed wave, and the
 height of the waveform was a proxy for the wing beat amplitude, and the
 frequency of this waveform was the wing beat frequency.
 Flies tended to gradually decrease their wing beat amplitude when the airstream
 was turned on (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-diff-odors"

\end_inset

b, left panel), though the wing beat amplitude did not change as much ((Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-diff-odors"

\end_inset

b, right panel).
 Switching airstreams in the absence of odorant did not evoke any strong
 response, either with the control airstream (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-diff-odors"

\end_inset

b, blue), or with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

odor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 airstream (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-diff-odors"

\end_inset

b, red).
 
\end_layout

